A longer pointing finger than ring finger means a lower risk of cancer
Men whose pointing finger is longer than the ring finger are obviously exposed to a lower risk of prostate cancer.
This is the surprising result of a study published on Wednesday by the British Journal of Cancer.
This is supposed to be related to the mirror of the male hormone testosterone.
"Our results show that the relative length of the fingers can serve as a simple test for the risk of prostate cancer and this, in particular, for men to sixty", said the co-author of the study, Ros Eeles, professor at the cancer research institute at the University of Warwick.
The finger could help determine which men should be subject to a prostate cancer test, especially when there are genetic risks or other risk factors, such as family health burdens, adds Mrs Eeles.
During the period 1994-2009, she and her colleagues in Britain pursued more than 1500 patients with prostate cancer, but at the same time 3000 healthy men.
For more than half of the participants in the study, the right-hand finger was shorter than the ring finger.
For these men the likelihood of prostate cancer was the same as for 19 percent of the men whose ring and pointing fingers were equal.
However, in men whose pointing finger was longer than the ring finger, this risk decreased by 33 percent, in men up to 87 percent.
The ratio of the length of the two fingers mentioned above, which are already in prenatal age, clearly reflects the different mirrors of gender hormones that the child was exposed to in the uterus.
Less testosterone corresponds to a longer pointing finger.
Earlier research revealed that the testosterone is accelerating the growth of prostate cancer.
Václav Pačes, leading Czech geneticist and former president of the Academy of Sciences, said that he was familiar with this study, yet he did not consider the relationship between the finger length and the cancer risk to date "completely proved".
